        <main>
            <p> The Digital BioLab web application was designed to help Hinton Scholar students manage their learning of AP<sup>®</sup> Biology. This mobile-friendly app takes advantage of student owned mobile devices. The design consists of a tablet optimized dashboard and a responsively enabled mobile version that connects students to their data, peers and instructors.
            </p>
            <p>
            <figure class="figure float-left"> <img class="figure-img img-fluid rounded gap-right" src="images/main/digital_biolab-4_320px.jpg" alt="Collaborative microscopy setup."> <figcaption class="figure-caption">Collaborative microscopy setup.</figcaption> </figure> The Digital BioLab is based upon several innovations piloted over the course of the last four years working with AP Biology classes from four Boston Public Schools. We explored changes to instructional practice with three key innovations in mind: 1) a <a href="http://hinton.harvardmedk12.wikispaces.net/">wiki environment</a> for sharing curriculum resources that increased communication between students and tutors and afforded rapid sharing of digitized laboratory data, 2) integration of digital probeware and instrumentation into hands-on AP Biology lab sessions hosted at Harvard Medical School, and 3) assessment of student understanding of major AP Biology themes and science practices using a combination of low-tech and high tech assessment tools. Lab teams used low-tech Post-it notes to design and share their own open inquiry investigations. High-tech tools such as the Nearpod app helped lab instructors track understanding of important experimental steps and key biological concepts. Piloting these new innovations created a 21st century science learning environment, provided practical insights on implementing <a href="http://www.nextgenscience.org/next-generation-science-standards">Next Generation Science Standards </a>and assisted educators with new instructional strategies adapted for the AP Biology curriculum. 
            </p>
