            <p>
            <figure class="figure float-right"><img class="figure-img img-fluid rounded gap-left" src="images/main/digital_biolab-1_320px.jpg" alt="Student responds to questions using their smart phone the lab."> <figcaption class="figure-caption text-right">Responding to questions with smartphone app.</figcaption> </figure> Two of the biggest trends impacting the education of today’s students are the rapid growth of social media platforms and the proliferation of mobile devices. The intersection of these two trends has produced what Gardner and Davis describe as the <a href="http://appgen.yupnet.org/"><book>App Generation.</book></a> We are exploring how to adapt a face-to-face science instruction model to meet the needs of these <em>connected</em> learners. The Digital BioLab project is researching the effect of using mobile technologies on student learning in an established AP Biology program at Harvard Medical School. Students and educators can use this customized mobile app and dashboard to enable student self-assessment of learning progress based on the AP Biology Big Ideas framework. This beta version contains four key modules: 
                <ol>
                    <li>Big Ideas Understanding</li>
                    <li>Wheel of Vernier Game App</li>
                    <li>Lab Data Viewer</li>
                    <li>Scientific Inquiry adapted Question Formulation Technique (QFT)</li>
                </ol> 
            Empowering students to track and reflect on their own learning has the potential to increase learner engagement, improve metacognition of scientific thinking and reinforce mastery of AP Biology practices. Project educators will have a new app-based formative assessment tool for implementing active learning environments that support science inquiry. 
